Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Modeling physical models with the Wolfram Language", "Title",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985867871823264*^9, 
  3.985867882275207*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a779d27a-84cd-478b-908d-\
d481ecc37c5d"],

Cell["Introducing PhysicsModelLink", "Subtitle",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985867884940029*^9, 
  3.985867899081184*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6a5320ec-6666-49cf-b282-\
cc7b389c3f9f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Writing Wolfram Language code with generative LLM models makes it possible \
to create more complex projects in less time. In this post I describe a new \
paclet called ",
 ButtonBox["PhysicsModelLink",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://www.wolframcloud.com/obj/arnoudbuzing/DeployedResources/\
Paclet/ArnoudBuzing/PhysicsModelLink/"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://www.wolframcloud.com/obj/arnoudbuzing/DeployedResources/Paclet/\
ArnoudBuzing/PhysicsModelLink/"],
 " that I created largely with agentic use of LLMs. For this project I used \
both the Antigravity IDE (from Google) and VS Code IDE (from Microsoft) with \
a mixture of LLM models, primarily Google Gemini, Claude Sonnet, and Claude \
Opus."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985867927883347*^9, 3.985868166709502*^9}, {
  3.985868199456356*^9, 3.9858681994564857`*^9}, {3.985868632950845*^9, 
  3.985868633293939*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2ff99ad9-78c3-4c64-8a8a-\
c80f3073690c"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The implementation of this paclet centers around a Rust physics engine \
called ",
 ButtonBox["Rapier",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://rapier.rs/docs/"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://rapier.rs/docs/"],
 ". The Wolfram Language code uses ",
 ButtonBox["LibraryLink",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://reference.wolfram.com/language/guide/LibraryLink.html"], 
    None},
  ButtonNote->"https://reference.wolfram.com/language/guide/LibraryLink.html"],
 " to call various Rust functions from that physics engine. Engineering the \
code in this way makes the computational steps very fast (at compiled Rust \
speeds) and exposes the higher level functions to the user with Wolfram \
Language modeling and visualizations functions\[LongDash]the best of both \
worlds."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985868237004888*^9, 
  3.985868488348771*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a752f8cb-05d9-4419-b9de-\
3d9f0b369657"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The development workflow largely happened in the chat interface of the IDE. \
The first step was to create the Wolfram Language paclet structure and create \
the Rust project crate to build the Rust dynamic library. The Rust code is \
used completely unmodified, with various low-level Wolfram LibraryLink \
functions calling the Rust functions. The first step was to create a very \
simple LibraryLink function, ",
 ButtonBox["RapierVersion",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/arnoudbuzing/PhysicsModelLink/blob/main/\
PhysicsModelLink/Kernel/PhysicsModelLink.wl#L17"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://github.com/arnoudbuzing/PhysicsModelLink/blob/main/\
PhysicsModelLink/Kernel/PhysicsModelLink.wl#L17"],
 ", which simply gets the library\[CloseCurlyQuote]s version number."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985868608689139*^9, 3.9858686678330393`*^9}, {
  3.985868801570183*^9, 
  3.9858689414273233`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"28de64c1-b2dc-4e88-973a-\
57a41805bc23"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The next major step was the create a complete set of low-level LibraryLink \
functions that call directly into the Rust library. When that was completed \
and tested, the user-facing Wolfram Language functions could be created using \
these lower level functions. In addition to that a few Wolfram Language level \
utility functions needed to be created. For example, the Rust physics engine \
computes object translations and rotations with quaternions, whereas the \
Wolfram Language uses transformation functions. An example of such a utility \
function is ",
 ButtonBox["QuaternionToTransformation",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/arnoudbuzing/PhysicsModelLink/blob/main/\
PhysicsModelLink/Kernel/PhysicsModelLink.wl#L32"], None},
  ButtonNote->
   "https://github.com/arnoudbuzing/PhysicsModelLink/blob/main/\
PhysicsModelLink/Kernel/PhysicsModelLink.wl#L32"],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9858689474144487`*^9, 
  3.9858692036161757`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a4d7d7da-07c6-4978-9526-\
37a50b58ae7b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The code for this project lives on ",
 ButtonBox["Github",
  BaseStyle->"Hyperlink",
  ButtonData->{
    URL["https://github.com/arnoudbuzing/PhysicsModelLink"], None},
  ButtonNote->"https://github.com/arnoudbuzing/PhysicsModelLink"],
 ". I compiled dynamic libraries for Windows and MacOS, with Linux support \
hopefully to follow in the near future. "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985868531190312*^9, 3.9858685805843067`*^9}, {
  3.9858692316979437`*^9, 
  3.985869247149488*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ba28aa44-1b75-4dd7-a9c8-\
7287c075d934"],

Cell["\<\
Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s take a look at a few examples. The first example is \
basically the \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Hello World\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] \
example of physical modeling: A bouncing ball. This example shows how to set \
up a model, display/plot it, and animate it over time.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.985868531190312*^9, 3.9858685805843067`*^9}, {
  3.9858692316979437`*^9, 
  3.985869314139504*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"c519d2e2-eee6-4848-997a-\
32303e3e0be0"],

